# Analyzing Network Performance Degradation During Cyber Attacks in Smart Grid Simulations (SGSim)

## Overview

This was my Bachelor Project in Cybersecurity at Noroff University College.

In this project, I investigated how cyberattacks affect communication and network performance in a simulated smart grid environment.

The main goal was to measure performance degradation using network metrics such as latency, jitter, packet loss, and IPDV.

## Project Objective

The aim of this project was to measure how cyberattacks affect communication and network performance in SGSim.

The project compared three scenarios:

* Baseline operation
* Denial of Service (DoS)
* False Data Injection (FDI)

## Technologies and Tools

* SmartGridSim (SGSim)
* Mininet
* Ubuntu virtual machine
* VMware Workstation
* Wireshark
* tshark
* Python
* pandas
* matplotlib
* Bash scripts

## Experimental Setup

The experiment was carried out in a controlled virtual environment.

Each scenario was repeated 12 times:

* 12 baseline runs
* 12 DoS runs
* 12 FDI runs

In total, 36 experiment runs were completed.

Network traffic was captured from the control-side interface, CONTROLSW-eth3. This point was used because it showed communication between the control center and the substations.

Each run lasted 180 seconds:

* 30 seconds stabilization
* 120 seconds normal operation or attack period
* 30 seconds post-stabilization

## Metrics Analyzed

The captured PCAP files were processed into CSV files and analyzed using Python.

The main metrics were:

* Latency
* Jitter
* Packet loss
* Inter-Packet Delay Variation (IPDV)

## Main Findings

The DoS scenario caused the largest impact on network performance and produced the highest delay variation.

The FDI scenario had less effect on timing performance but affected data integrity.

Packet loss remained at 0% during all test scenarios.

